@mrdoob the production case for this change might not be as strong as the test one (which would be that there is test pollution any time a renderer is initialized) -- but I believe the strongest case for prod is that no other JS framework that I've used/seen automatically logs out purely informational content like this without allowing you to turn it off?

Regardless, the test situation is much more relevant for test runners that will log out things like this.

_Aside: loving this library and the work you've done :metal:_

@WestLangley 
![screen shot 2015-01-02 at 9 46 27 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/296167/5598083/4a4e02a6-9264-11e4-8063-2fa621eaa83d.png)

Notice the context of the debugger is changed to the result of the jsfiddle

To everyone else:

``` javasript
console.realLog = console.log;
console.log = function () {
        if (arguments[0] != 'THREE.WebGLRenderer')
                console.realLog.apply (console, arguments);
};
```

[😎](http://jsfiddle.net/95t964o0/67/)

@WestLangley & @mrdoob - I _REALLY_ think this should be a debug flag. 

Having this constantly logged in my console is noise that I don't need ( and I'm a crazy person and hate not a clean console ;) ). 

Not to mention, whats next every library starts doing this? Now I've got 100 console logs that mean nothing... just my 10c
